{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_jerome_ver01/data/sn90061663/00280779684/1908050701/0982.xml":{"full_text":"77; c Hlcli Hill Tribune,\nGL'O. II. I0Y KM.. rublh-hcr.\nrum ntu Missorui.\nEnglish and American Abuses.\nThere Is one form of the abuse of\nwealth in politic from which Kngland\nI prtseut Is comparatively free. Rhe\nleu not Buffer from the problems cf\ncorporation In politics. It Is a rare\nthins for a statutory company, mirti,\nfor Instance, a a railway company, or\nfur a joint stock company of any kind,\nto contribute from Ita funds to the\ncampaign chest of political parties.\nThe thing in not unknown- there wa\ncase about a year ago In which the\ndirectors of on of the great railway\ncompanies wore found to have sub\nfcrlbcl to the moderate party In the\nLonda county council elections. Hut\non th whole the practice is frowned\nupon both by public opinion and by\nthe general sense of the commercial\ncommunity. Nor does the political ne\ncessity for It exist in England. Three\nreasons, I believe, writes Sydney\nBrooks In Harper's Weekly, are usu\nally given to explain the Intimacy of\nthe all'ance between corporations and\npolitics In the United States. The\nfirst is that In an expanding, half de\nveloped country the number of good\nthings to be picked up In the way of\nconcessions is beyond comparison\nirreater than In such a land as Eng\nland. The second reason w hy the\ntrusts cannot leave politics alone In\nAmerica Is that politics cannot leave\nthe trusts alone, and their action and\nreaction seem to be enormously Inten\nsified and complicated by the Ameri\ncan system of government In self-contained\ncompartments.\nSomebody rather pertinently sug\ngests that people should have tele\nphone hours as well as hours when\nthey receive callers. The telephone\nbreaks In on everybody's time In a\nway that would not be tolerated If the\npeople who use it came in person.\nThis is true in the home, in business\nestablishments and in offices. A pa\ntient ia in a doctor' office, for exam\nTie, keeping a special engagement and\nwith his own time limited, or he is in\na dentist's chair, when th telephone\nbell rings and the doctor or dentist\nleaTes hlra and engages in a long con\nversation over the wire. Everyone,\ncomments the Indianapolis Star, has\nbeen Irritated by the tyianny of th's\nInstrument and the manner in which\nIt penetrates privacy and trespasses on\ntime. A system of telephone etiquette\nought to be established.\nCongressman Olmsteal asked the\nagricultural committee of the house to\ntell him how much it costs to keep a\nben a year. Whether he want to keep\na hen and does not wish to go at it\nblindly or whether he desires to en\ngage In a statistical calculation in re\ngard to the poultry industry is not\nknown, nor is it important. The sig\nnificant thing Is that not a member of\nthe committee could tell him what he\nwanted to know. One ventured the\nopinion that the \"keep\" of a hen costs\n\"next to nothing,\" while another fixed\nthe expense at $1.75 a year. What is\nan agricultural committee for, asks the\nIndianapolis Star, if it is not primed\non subjects like this; and what does it\ncost to keep a hen, anyway?\nIs profanity on the streets and in\nother public places getting to be more\nprevalent in this community than\nelsewhere? asks the lloston Herald.\nAn Intelligent and observant visitor\nhere says it Is. He has traveled fur\nand wide and he testifies that one\nhears the name of the Almighty taken\nin vain more frequently by men and\nboys in our eastern cities, and particu\nlarly in lloston, than lu any of the less\nboasted or boastful centcts of culiuie\nand civilization. This I a rather ii.-rt-ous\nIndict ment of cur nmnuer ami\nmorals. If it Is warranted by the facts\nIt might be well to rail for tin) more\nrl&id and vigorous enforcement of the\nancient law on the subject. It covers\nthe offence.\nIly the retirement o lr. Kcglnald\nHeber Kit from tho Mersey professor\nship of the theory and practice of by\nsirs at the Harvard medical school\nthat Institution loi-es the active sen\nIces of one of the most distinguished\nmembers of its staff. He is generall,\nrecognized in his profession as stand\ning at the head of It in this section of\nthe country at least.\nThe Pima Indians, who Ihe on the\ntauks of the Gila river pronounced\nSpauitli Heela), are the mot: civilized\nof any North American Indians. They\nlive in liOiscs. manufacture useful ar\nticks and are known for i-lmpliclty il\ncharacter, peacef ulnesa and honesty.\nThe new locomotive shops which the\nGrand Trunk of Canada system Is\nbuilding ;tt 1 fie Crock, Mich., will\nbe among tl.e largest lu the country.\nThe i!i;u l.ino hop, which has a length\nof over SiiO feet, is to be built entirely\n-f ht. i l, brick and cement.\n\"The vertti'foi in iippcndu Is th only\n(Mi)!? In nature, so far ttj is known,\nthat Is absolutely useless.\" ay the\nLancet. Absolutely varies.! And it\nliss helped many a smjjtvn out of\nHIE SIXTIETH CONGRESS\nCONDENSED NEWS FROM THE\nNATIONAL CAPITOL.\nThs Most Important Items Gathered\nFrom Each Day's Eesdon cf\nSenate and House.\nWashington. I. C. As llio result of\na series of conferences between Re\npublican leaders iu the house, tho Inst\nof which was hold Wednesday, Repre\nsentative. Vreelaud of New York late\nWednesday introduced a bill to take\nthe place of the currency bill present\ned by him last week. In the new bill,\nwhich Is declared to represent th\nviews of a fubslantial majority of the\nRepublican members and which is the\nmeasure that will be presented to the\nconference of the Republican of the\nhouse to be held within a few days,\nnothing is left of the Aldrlch currency\nbill except the provision for the pay\nment of interest on government de\nposits in national banks. The provis\nions for the issuance of emergency\ncurrency on coriorate bonds are cn\ntirely swept away.\nThe new bill provides for the for\nmation of national clearing house as\nsociations by not less than ten na\ntional banks having an aggregate capi\ntal and surplus of not less than 3,\n000.000. A tat ot 4 per cent on emer\ngency circulation based on clearing\nhouse association securities is pro\nvided for the first month, this tax to\nbe increased 1 per cent each month\nuntil it reaches 10 per cent w here it Is\nto remain until the circulation Is re\ntired. Another section of the bill provides\nfor the creation of a currency commis\nsion to consist of six members of tho\nhouse, six of the senate and six to be\nappointed by the president.\nWashington, D. C. More evidence\ntending to show that there Is a com\nblna'ic n of paper manufacturers to fix\nthe price of news print paper in the\nUnited States was adduced Wednes\nday before the special committee ot\nthe house which is investigating the\nsubject of duty on wood pulp and print\npaper as affecting the price In the\nUnited States. Mr. John Norris, of\nthe New York Times and represent\ning the paper committee of the Ameri\ncan Newspaper Publishers' association,\ncontinued his testimony and presented\nnumerous letters and documents to\nbear out his contention. Apparently\nthe committee was particularly im\npressed with the annual statement of\nthe International Paper company for\nthe fiscal year ended June CO, 1907,\nshowing an increased cost of produc\ntion of CO cents a ton as against the\nraise of price of paper of 12 a ton.\nChairman Mann, appreciating the Im\nportance of this testimony announced\nthat he would go to the bottom to as\ncertain the cause of so large an ln\ncrens.j In the price of paper.\nApplause From Both Sides.\nWashington, D. C. Ostensibly con\nsidering the sundry civil appropriation\nbill, the house devoted most of Its\ntime Tuesday to speeches covering a\nwide range of subjects and concluded\nthe session by giving an attentive\nhearing to the president' special mes\nsage. Although nearly every member\nhad read the message in the newspa\npers, a large number remained la their\nseats carefully following the words ot\nthe reading clerk. When the portion\nof the message referring to the multi\nmillionaire \"whose son is a fool and\nhis daughter a foreign princess\" was\nreached tliere was a storm of applause\nequally prominent on both Bides of the\nhouse.\nWhitney Wrote the Letters.\nWashington. D. C Fred It. Whit\nney formerly nn attorney for the Lake\nTorpedo Iloat company, Thursday con\nfessed that he bad written the anony\nmous letters which have figured In the\nUlley submarine boat Investigation. It\nwas announced at the close of Thurs\nday's session that ther would be no\nmore open mcitlnt; by the committee.\nSecretary Straj Re Appointed.\nWnst.lnrton, I. President I'ooac\nvelt In a formal letter Thursday noti\nfied Secretary Htraus of the depart\nment of commerce and labor that he\nhad re-appolnied him for another term\nof six fear as one of the American\nmembers of the Permanent Court of\nArbitration at The Hague.\nWarner Unable to Finish Speech.\nWashington, D. C. llccause of a\nseitre cold, which lias confined hirr\nto his home, Senator Warner did not\nresume his speech on the Hrowusvllle\naffra In the senate WeJnenday Mr.\nWarner's m-m. will now be read by\nsoiu.i i-ulleugue and In that manner\ncompleted.\nAnxious About Cleveland.\nNew York. The Evening World\ngave prominence Friday to the fol\nlowing: \"There Is a report current\nin flMitiflal circle, emanating from\nthe to'linr if the F4 'jtubin Lit As\nsurance n-K-lety, that Form, r PreM\ndent U'Ofer Cteielan 4 is a sufferer\nfrom raui f of ioma h suel that\nbis cae has been runuuncc hop,\nless by specialists.\"\nMore Tucker Evidence.\nTopeka. Kan F. A. Fauht. former\nsuperintendent of refiner), s of the\nUncle Sain Oil runiaiiy, tehtified\nThursday in tee cane m.-aiui-t H. If\nTucker, charging him with using-thu\nmuils In a fraud scheme, thai at the\ntime Tucker was sending out eircut-i:s\nrlalmini; the company was Making big\nprofiis, it would l.ave been lmjolhlt\nto have operuled tha three at a refit,\nowiiis to j-oor market, small capacity\nand local ion. Tho government ton\neumed tlm mtlre day but upsets to\nEnUli Friday ly loou.\nTHE WATER\nThe Fisherman la Losing His\nWOULD SIDETRACK PANIC\nST. LOUIS MEN TRY TO HASTEN\nRETURN OF PROSPERITY.\nHope to Keep Dinner Pail Full, Pay\nCar Going, Factory Busy, Work\nmen Employed and Wages Up.\nSt. Louis, Mo. A business organi\nratlon to be known as ths National\nProsperity association of St. Louis\nhas been formed as the result of a\nconference held by business, nien here\nduring the past three days, and Fri\nday nil)t a formal address was Issued\nto the business Interests of the coun\ntry. It is proposed to extend the rami\nfications of the association through\nout the country for the betterment of\nall classes of business.\nIt Is stated that the association has\nfor Its object the encouragement of a\nreturn of prosperity and uplift Ins of\nbusiness Interests generally.\nThe officers of the association com\nprise the executive committee and\nthey are Chairman K. C. Simmons,\nformerly president of the Simmons\nHardware company, and vice chair\nman. W. K. Ulxby, formerly president\nof the American Car and Foundry\ncompany.\nIu the formal n.l lret-s Issued Fri\nday night it Is set forth that the pur\npones of the National Prosperity as\nsociation of St. Louis arc:\nTo keep the dinner pal! full; to\nkeep the pay car going; to keep the\nfactory busy; to keep the workmen\nemployed, and to keep the present\nwag's up.\nRefused List of Stockholders.\nLincoln, Neb The Western Union\nTelRraph company Wednesday re\nfused to file a list of the stockholders\nof the corporation with the Nebraska\nstate railway commission. Secretary\nPerkins was Instructed to Inform the\ncompi.ny that the information must be\nfurthcoming or a suit would be start\ned. The state law provide a penalty\nof not less than $r.ii;1 nor more than\n$5,000 for each refusal to furnish data\ndemanded by t he commission.\nA Lumber Merger