April, lyt'S. show the total receipts to\nhave been ti:'., 919, 321 and the expendi\ntures $j9,SSS.7M. leafing a deficit for\nthe month of nearly S lO.frtm.Ono. a de\nficit for the ten months of the pres\nrnt fiscal year of $r,l,C4t,'.13. as\nagainst a surplus for the correspond\ning period last year of J'i'1. 473,7.11.\nThe statement shows that during these\nlast ten months there has been a fall\ning off in the receipts of $11 .3S7.3C2.\nand an Increase In expenditures of\n$CG.722.8'H, making a difference In the\ncondition of the treasury of $le8,120,\nZCG. This amount is likely to be In\ncreased to $123.0t'0,OiX by the close\nof the fiscal year. During April the\nreceipts from customs amounted to\n$2.5C2,(i'-0. which U a loss as com\npare! wiifi April, 1907. of nenrly $7,\ntX'O.OoO. Internal revenue receipt\n$lS,rSj,3CS; loss. $2.CtS,\"00.\nENJOINS 16 RAILROADS.\nAttorney General West SeeWs to Keep\nLiquor Out of Indian Territory.\nArdmore, Ok. Attorney Ceneral\nCharlr West Tuesday filed nn Injunc\ntion suit in the district court of Car\nter county agatr.st 10 railroads and ex\npress companies In the state to re\nstrain them from carrying liquor\nshipments Into that section of the state\nformerly known a.i the Indian Terri\ntory. The suit Is based upon an agree\nment between the railroad und the\nfederal government, made prior to\nstatehood, when the railroads and ex\npress companies agreed not to bring\nliijuor Into the Indian Territory.\nThe Indians' treaties with the fed\neral government provided that intoxi\ncants should newr be sold in the In\ndlan country even after the lands had\nbeen opened to settlement. The state,\naccording to the attorney general,\nagreed In its acceptance of the en\nabling act to respect all treaties made\nby the federal government with In\ndian citizens of (he state.\nWill File Choi Suits.\nK ir.ras City. .Mo. Official of seven\nrailroads who were subpoenaed to ap\npear before the federi-l grand Jury\nhere Thursday to testify lu regard to\nfreight rates, were Wednesday noti\nfied not to rep.,rt. A S. Van Valken\nburg. United States dlslrlct attorney,\ndimlcd the ciiiimi.il proc litis\nagainst the railroads and announce\nth-t he will f:ie civil suits.\nTh United Christian Party.\"\nItock Island. III.-The United Chris\ntl.m parly held It national conven\ntion Friday afternoon and nominated\nllev. I'anlel It. Turney, ,,f 1 ;,tur.\nIII for president and U S Cofl'm of\nFort Podge, loa. for lee president.\nThe platform declares for the d -ca-lojv.ie\nar l tl.e gulden rule as the basis\nof all laws and upholds female fcUf\nfr:i;e.\nA Federal Judge Res.gne.\nM.'skoee... ok United Stales Judge\nHa'pti K. Campbell, of the eastern dis\ntrict of Oklahoma, has forwarded bis\nrclctiatlon to the n'torney general,\ngivlu,' ns hl3 reason that he prefers to\nresume tlie practice of law.\nThe Fleet At Monterey.\nMonterey. Cab The Atlantic fleet\nof bittleidips steanie.t m here Friday\ntc ghe Muiiterey. peninsula of Cali\nfornia, a place In th- Mutory of the\nAmertci.n mivy record breaking cruise\niiroui I the world.\nLeithman Must Explain.\nWellington. I). itepr. sentatlve\nMurdoch of Kansas Friday took up\nwIMi the slate department tf-e alleged\nr.ctiou of Ambassador Ul.ihman In\nt nde.. voring to Induce Mrs. liernarl\nWarkentlu to tAn a paper 1 cle.ii'ln,;\nthe Turkish prince .o aii i.lentally\nshot I er husband 011 a railroad lra'11\nnear i,imacux, frcm piosecui Ion. Tb\nslate d. 1 urtuieiit mil request An\nplanatlon of the n I,...., ador. TI18\nluafer has not gone to f..r as fi!lii\na formal cumpUllit rKaltis. Mr. Leish.\nm m\nA ROYAL MARRIACE.\nPrince Wilhrlm of Sweden and Crand\nDuchess Marl of Russia.\n8t. Petersburg l'rlncn Wlllielm of\nBwodeti, second on of King tiustavo,\nthe popular sailor prince who ftslted\nAmerica In 1907, was married Sunday\nafternoon to (Irand Puches Marl\nPavltovua, cuiihIh of the emperor of\nKnssla and daughter of (.Irand luika\nPaul Alexan lrovitch.\nThe ceremony took place at Tsaru\nkoe Selo and was aoconipanb-d by all\nthe pomp and brilliant display char\nacteristic of the most stalely court in\nFurope.\nThe beginning of the nuptial cere\nmonies was announced by the firing of\nfive guns simultaneously at nine\no'clock Sunday morning by the battery\nat Tsarskoe-Selo and by the fortress\nof St. Peter and St. Paul In St. Peters\nburg. This was but the beginning of\nthe noisy acclamation, for the thunder\nof salutes was heard almost uninter\nruptedly throughout the afternoon and\nthe evening.\nA New Refinery Promised Tulsa.\nOklahoma City, Ok. At a banquet\ntendered the Tulsa Iioosters Saturday\nnight a telegram was receive! from\nRobert (lalbreath, the oil refiner, stat\ning that Galbnath and associates\nhave secur-nl a site In weft Tulsa,\nupon which they w ill erect one of the\nbiggest. Independent oil refineries la\nthe United States. Tho statement I\nalso made that an eight Inch pipe lino\nwill be bulit from Tulsa to tho Paid\nHill pool and It will pass thrTiiKh the\nKed Fork and Giecn field where Gal\nbreath and his associates have large\ninterests.\ntn Interest cf Postal Progress.\nWashington. I). C. It Is announce!\nthat several of the leading member\nof tho senate and house will address\nthe meeting to be held on Tuesday\nnight of this week In the Interest ot\npostal legislation being urged by the\nPostal Progressive league and other\norganizations. The recommendations\nmade by Postmaster Ceneral Meyer,\nIncluding the establishment of a par\ncels post on I urai routes and of a pos\ntal savings bank will be indorsed by\nthe meeting.\nGrover Cleveland Improving.\nI.akewood. N. J. The condition ot\nformer President Grover Cleveland,\nwho is said by his physicians to be\nsuffering from acute indigestion, con\ntinued to show dally Improvement, ac\ncording to Mrs. Cleveland, who ex\npresses the hop that the progress of\nher husband' recovery may permit\nan early return to Prlucetoa. The pa\ntient peut a quiet Sunday at the Luko\nwood hotel nd Mrs. Cle-rSni ex1\npnssed herself as pleased with th\nprogress madi!.\nMay Abolish Racing In New Orlean.\nNew Orleans, I .a A campaign to\nabolish racing la Louisiana, hacked by\nsome of the wealthiest and most In\nfluential residents of the state, will be\nlaunched before tlm legislature which\nmeets at ltatou Kouge one week from\nnext Monday. The attempt will be\nmade to suppress absolutely every\nform of betting al racing tracks, and\nIt Is understood that this will result la\nthe permanent closing of the track.\nAnother St. Louis Suicide.\nSt. IaiuI.i. Mo After standing for a\nmoment with bared head and uplifted\nhands as though In prayer, an uniden\ntified and well dressed young man\ncommltte 1 suicide Sunday by Jumping\nInto the Mississippi river at the foot\nof Tyler street.\nM. E. Conference ta Meet.\nHaltimoie, Ml. The general con\nference of the M-thixllst Kplscopal\nchurch, the governing body of thst il\"\nnomination will assemble u Lyric\nhall, this city, for Its quadrennial ses\nsion at ten o'clock oil Wednesday\nmorning rcL\nRussian Certificates Recognized.\nSt. Petersburg --It Is nun. mined by\nthe tnl;:!i;:er of finance that the Unl'e\nState has agreed to teconui.e the\nItusslati bourse committee's certin\nCates fixing the custom value of 1'tc\nslau gin.. Is Imported Into America A\nsimilar r:v already has bei-u\nglinted German cbambet of com\nmerce. Mny Die In Hotel Fir.\nFort Wayne, I tel. Ten known dead,\nmany missing and 13 si-i'musly in\nJure! is the result of a lire th.nl d\ntroed tho new Avelina hot.l, Fort\nWayne's principal hostelry at an\nearly hour Sun lav. Chief of Police\nAiicketibruck sail Sunday afternoon he\nbelief e4 20 bodies Welu Mi l 111 tho\nruins.\nEulogies In the House Sunday.\nWashington. l. C Addresses eul.i\nllftie of the life, character and public\nservices of the late United Mates ren\nator Stephen K. Mallory and Senator\nWilliam J. Itryan of Florida were d.v\nJlvc r-d Sunday lu the house of r. pre-\nell!4!le.\nTaft'